Scott: But then in the back, for some reason, I guess I don't know what its history was, but they were like preserving the history of the magazine in this tiny black and white section in the back where they had like these weird, quirky Alice and Bob articles that would be more at home in something like The Computist, right?

807
00:53:42,362 --> 00:53:43,779
Scott: Or a Dragon Magazine kind of deal.

808
00:53:43,840 --> 00:53:45,499
Rym: I forgot all about Alice and Bob.

809
00:53:45,660 --> 00:53:45,881
Rym: Right.

810
00:53:46,383 --> 00:53:46,624
Scott: Yeah.

811
00:53:46,825 --> 00:53:50,380
Scott: So they had this quirky little area in the back that they just kept preserving.

812
00:53:51,441 --> 00:53:52,425
Scott: I stopped reading it.

813
00:53:52,525 --> 00:53:55,396
Scott: It became a smaller magazine and a thinner one at some point.

814
00:53:55,436 --> 00:53:56,420
Scott: And then I'm pretty sure it died.

815
00:53:56,561 --> 00:53:57,227
Rym: I didn't read it.

816
00:53:57,549 --> 00:53:58,639
Rym: Like I would read it like...

817
00:53:58,820 --> 00:54:00,975
Scott: I never read one that wasn't a big fat one.

818
00:54:00,995 --> 00:54:01,035
Scott: So...

819
00:54:01,700 --> 00:54:01,790
Rym: Yeah.

820
00:54:02,820 --> 00:54:12,040
Scott: And I never got... And basically the thing is that magazine, despite being mostly ads, taught me, right, indirectly how to build a computer.

821
00:54:12,140 --> 00:54:18,580
Scott: I built my first computer by looking at Computer Shopper and using just common sense.

822
00:54:18,780 --> 00:54:22,900
Scott: Like I see a picture of RAM and I see... I finally can see a picture of a motherboard.

823
00:54:23,080 --> 00:54:26,260
Scott: That's probably the first time I ever saw a PC motherboard, right?

824
00:54:26,680 --> 00:54:29,839
Scott: And I saw... Well, no, I guess I opened up the IBM and saw it in there, but...

825
00:54:30,660 --> 00:54:30,958
Rym: Yeah, for me.

826
00:54:31,100 --> 00:54:36,740
Scott: I saw the picture... I saw a picture of a motherboard and I saw what RAM looked like and I saw all the different things they were selling.

827
00:54:36,800 --> 00:54:38,165
Scott: They were selling power supplies.

828
00:54:38,205 --> 00:54:42,920
Scott: They were selling, you know, like hard drives and I saw the things, pictures of them.

829
00:54:43,601 --> 00:54:48,220
Scott: And I could... I was able to figure out from that, like, this is what I need to make a computer.

830
00:54:48,561 --> 00:54:48,822
Rym: Yeah.

831
00:54:48,962 --> 00:54:53,360
Rym: I even would look at... There was an ad for a computer and it listed all the components of the computers.

832
00:54:53,520 --> 00:54:55,940
Rym: Now I knew what things I had to buy to make my own computer.

833
00:54:56,381 --> 00:54:59,931
Scott: And one of the companies that had an ad in there was TC Computer.

834
00:54:59,951 --> 00:55:03,340
Scott: I don't think they exist anymore, which stood for Treasure Chest Computer.

835
00:55:03,480 --> 00:55:11,500
Scott: And I went to their website and with the combined with the magazine and their website and the ads, I bought the parts for my first computer.

836
00:55:12,081 --> 00:55:16,580
Scott: They actually sent me the 8-bit motherboard with the Pentium 3 already in it.

837
00:55:16,721 --> 00:55:18,859
Scott: So I didn't have to do that part, but I had to do everything else.

838
00:55:19,481 --> 00:55:21,088
Scott: And I got all these parts.

839
00:55:21,209 --> 00:55:23,760
Scott: I got the right parts successfully.

840
00:55:24,341 --> 00:55:30,420
Scott: And then I figured out how to put them together by common sense and looking at what fit in what hole and what cables they sent me.

841
00:55:30,781 --> 00:55:34,339
Scott: And I successfully built a computer by looking at ads in a magazine.

842
00:55:35,280 --> 00:55:39,499
Rym: I feel like by that... Because I didn't build a computer until the year 2000, right before I went to RIT.

843
00:55:40,340 --> 00:55:41,618
Rym: I think I mostly used...

844
00:55:41,740 --> 00:55:42,700
Scott: This was in 1998 or 1999.

845
00:55:42,700 --> 00:55:46,980
Rym: I think by then I used, like, the old Tom's Hardware and egghead.com.

846
00:55:48,280 --> 00:55:50,047
Scott: Yeah, I used... This was 1999, yeah.

847
00:55:50,689 --> 00:55:53,540
Scott: So I was a computer shopper, so that was a thing.

848
00:55:53,560 --> 00:56:01,219
Rym: But the one that really got me was not Computer Shopper because it was... The 90s, like the late 90s, is when I really got deep into PCs.

849
00:56:01,500 --> 00:56:06,100
Rym: Before that, I was mostly interested in the software because I couldn't afford or build or mess with the hardware.

850
00:56:06,320 --> 00:56:08,060
Rym: So I lived in the software world.

851
00:56:08,300 --> 00:56:11,116
Rym: But in the 90s, late 90s, I wanted to build computers.

852
00:56:11,136 --> 00:56:11,920
Rym: I was getting into gaming.

853
00:56:12,100 --> 00:56:13,098
Rym: Like, the hardware mattered more to me.

854
00:56:13,580 --> 00:56:23,100
Rym: So Maximum PC was the one I read because it was the flashy magazine that had the articles talking about the fancy, newest nonsense that I definitely could not afford.

855
00:56:23,921 --> 00:56:30,180
Scott: If Maximum PC still existed, they would be the ones with, like, the cases with the cooling systems and the lights and that kind of stuff.

856
00:56:30,420 --> 00:56:30,751
Rym: Absolutely.

857
00:56:30,772 --> 00:56:30,999
Rym: Absolutely.

858
00:56:31,140 --> 00:56:33,118
Scott: That was the atmosphere of Maximum PC.

859
00:56:33,520 --> 00:56:40,520
Rym: But it had, like, this... Every issue had this overview of, like, what's the latest in the world of computing?

860
00:56:40,721 --> 00:56:44,100
Rym: And that's how I stayed on top of things way more than the internet in that era.

861
00:56:45,762 --> 00:56:49,760
Rym: And it also would have a lot of articles talking about how hardware worked, which Computer Shopper never had.

862
00:56:50,281 --> 00:56:54,995
Rym: And that... Maximum PC... To be clear, I never subscribed to that magazine.

863
00:56:55,396 --> 00:56:56,820
Rym: I would read it in the bookstore.

864
00:56:58,360 --> 00:56:59,799
Rym: Most of these I read in bookstores.

865
00:57:00,560 --> 00:57:07,780
Rym: The only one I got delivered and subscribed to was PC Gamer, which really we should talk about more on a Wednesday or a Tuesday episode.

866
00:57:08,261 --> 00:57:10,791
Scott: PC Gamer was mostly video game magazine.

867
00:57:11,112 --> 00:57:13,060
Scott: It was the same as a GamePro or anything else.

868
00:57:13,240 --> 00:57:18,040
Scott: It just only talked about PC games and included a CD because it was talking about PC games.

869
00:57:18,141 --> 00:57:19,718
Rym: PC Gamer came with a disc.

870
00:57:22,084 --> 00:57:23,218
Rym: Eventually it came with a CD.

871
00:57:24,401 --> 00:57:29,780
Scott: But it came with demos of games, sometimes full games, because you can do that when it's PC games.

872
00:57:29,920 --> 00:57:33,180
Scott: You couldn't really provide an NES cartridge with a Nintendo Power magazine.

873
00:57:33,460 --> 00:57:34,639
Rym: But I guess my point there is that...

874
00:57:34,720 --> 00:57:36,772
Scott: It also talked about hardware in there as well.

875
00:57:36,833 --> 00:57:38,040
Scott: So it was, like, a double deal.

876
00:57:38,761 --> 00:57:42,080
Scott: They had game reviews and they had hardware stuff.

877
00:57:42,120 --> 00:57:43,669
Rym: Except I barely read PC Gamer.

878
00:57:43,730 --> 00:57:45,299
Rym: I just wanted that disc.

879
00:57:46,143 --> 00:57:50,220
Scott: I bought a few PC gamers off the shelf at the bookstore to get the disc.

880
00:57:51,422 --> 00:57:53,177
Scott: I never subscribed to it.

881
00:57:53,378 --> 00:57:53,580
Scott: Anyway.

882
00:57:55,002 --> 00:57:59,860
Scott: So you had your zines that were sort of... I guess the biggest zine was 2600.

883
00:57:59,860 --> 00:58:01,640
Scott: It was still somewhat alive.

884
00:58:01,740 --> 00:58:03,320
Rym: It's actually the only one I read.

885
00:58:03,780 --> 00:58:10,160
Rym: I would get the text of issues of 2600 from a local BBS that I would dial into.

886
00:58:10,160 --> 00:58:16,000
Scott: 2600 was big enough that actually they would have issues at the bookstore, on the shelf, with the other magazines.

887
00:58:16,162 --> 00:58:17,840
Scott: Like at the Barnes and Noble or whatever.

888
00:58:18,404 --> 00:58:18,940
Scott: Or the Borders.

889
00:58:19,862 --> 00:58:22,520
Scott: I actually have a book that was published at some point.

890
00:58:22,680 --> 00:58:24,750
Scott: It's like best of 2600 collection.

891
00:58:24,770 --> 00:58:26,820
Scott: Like this huge fat book that's on my shelf over there.

892
00:58:27,720 --> 00:58:32,319
Scott: But 2600 started out as the phone freaking zine.

893
00:58:32,860 --> 00:58:34,489
Rym: Yeah, which we were on the tail.

894
00:58:34,529 --> 00:58:36,500
Rym: We were pretty young when that was dying out.

895
00:58:36,500 --> 00:58:37,578
Scott: We were too young for that, yeah.

896
00:58:37,981 --> 00:58:41,440
Scott: So it was coming out of that scene.

897
00:58:41,700 --> 00:58:47,020
Scott: So it has an origin that was really sort of hardcore and ultra nerdy and whatnot.

898
00:58:47,781 --> 00:58:52,320
Scott: But as time went on, the content didn't really get away from that.

899
00:58:52,540 --> 00:59:00,480
Scott: The content was still articles about deep technical specific stuff in different areas.

900
00:59:02,043 --> 00:59:04,660
Scott: But it was less underground.

901
00:59:04,981 --> 00:59:06,006
Scott: People knew about it.

902
00:59:06,106 --> 00:59:08,436
Scott: You could buy it literally at Borders books.

903
00:59:08,476 --> 00:59:09,360
Scott: There it fucking is.

904
00:59:09,560 --> 00:59:11,400
Scott: It was being published properly.

905
00:59:11,780 --> 00:59:16,440
Rym: It had much less of a counterculture street cred by that point.

906
00:59:17,241 --> 00:59:20,660
Scott: Right, and it wasn't doing so much the illegal type contents.

907
00:59:21,361 --> 00:59:23,300
Scott: Here's how to make free phone calls type stuff.

908
00:59:23,781 --> 00:59:29,140
Scott: Even though it was still deep technical topics of various computing and phone nature.

909
00:59:30,502 --> 00:59:35,620
Scott: So 2600 really, I think, I'm not sure how or to what extent it still exists.

910
00:59:36,302 --> 00:59:40,040
Scott: But it does have a historical importance to it.

911
00:59:40,600 --> 00:59:45,980
Scott: And is kind of representative, especially the earlier issues of what all those other zines were kind of like.

912
00:59:46,760 --> 00:59:53,800
Rym: Yeah, it's interesting because that was an era when I would read old 2600s but not more recent ones.

913
00:59:54,161 --> 01:00:01,439
Rym: And I was mostly interested in the stories and the technology of freaking and all the old stuff that I mostly missed out on.

914
01:00:02,664 --> 01:00:04,240
Scott: You didn't get to do it, but you learned about it.

915
01:00:04,260 --> 01:00:05,045
Rym: I got to do it a little bit.

916
01:00:05,105 --> 01:00:07,680
Rym: I did get a red box to work when I was in middle school.

917
01:00:09,163 --> 01:00:10,673
Rym: But that's just the one that plays the tones.

918
01:00:10,713 --> 01:00:11,639
Rym: that makes a payphone work.

919
01:00:12,061 --> 01:00:13,217
Rym: That was a really easy thing to do.

920
01:00:15,401 --> 01:00:16,820
Scott: It would work on an old payphone.

921
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:22,500
Rym: Yeah, it totally worked on old payphones up until our early days in middle school in some parts of the US.

922
01:00:23,347 --> 01:00:24,720
Rym: That definitely doesn't work anymore.

923
01:00:25,460 --> 01:00:29,640
Scott: There was another set of magazines that I'd never bought or read at all, but I knew about them.

924
01:00:30,181 --> 01:00:32,120
Rym: Like PC Magazine, all that stuff?

925
01:00:32,380 --> 01:00:33,464
Scott: Right, PC Magazine.

926
01:00:33,504 --> 01:00:35,311
Scott: I think the ZD had one.

927
01:00:36,254 --> 01:00:37,740
Scott: CNET might have had one also.

928
01:00:38,440 --> 01:00:42,680
Scott: And basically those magazines read the way those websites read.

929
01:00:43,340 --> 01:00:50,859
Scott: These sort of popular articles about what's going on in the world of personal computing and stuff.

930
01:00:51,684 --> 01:00:55,401
Rym: Oh, CNET shut down their magazine in 2019.

931
01:00:55,401 --> 01:00:57,048
Scott: Okay.

932
01:00:57,148 --> 01:01:00,020
Scott: You go to CNET.com and look at the articles.

933
01:01:00,681 --> 01:01:04,880
Scott: Or go to ZDNET, if that still exists, and read the articles or any of those places.

934
01:01:05,300 --> 01:01:09,340
Scott: That's what those magazines were like, only full of ads, obviously, and on paper.

935
01:01:10,861 --> 01:01:13,840
Scott: And so I'd only read them if I was in a dentist's office.

936
01:01:14,021 --> 01:01:20,120
Scott: And they mostly appealed to these people who were not ultra nerdy, like you're going to program a computer.

937
01:01:20,562 --> 01:01:23,296
Scott: But you're an uncle who's got money.

938
01:01:24,260 --> 01:01:25,679
Rym: It was everyone's uncle who read these things.

939
01:01:26,280 --> 01:01:27,570
Scott: Yeah, you're into computers.

940
01:01:27,611 --> 01:01:28,820
Scott: You care about computers.

941
01:01:29,321 --> 01:01:33,360
Scott: You got your computer as a little hobby, but you're not programming.

942
01:01:33,500 --> 01:01:38,780
Scott: You're not going lower than simply going to CompUSA to have some fun.

943
01:01:39,422 --> 01:01:44,339
Rym: I would say that those magazines, all the CNET adjacent magazines, there were so many of them.

944
01:01:44,760 --> 01:01:48,060
Rym: They were the things that might be in a dentist's office and you read out of boredom.

945
01:01:48,522 --> 01:01:51,859
Rym: Or the people who liked them seemed to read them more for entertainment than knowledge.

946
01:01:52,902 --> 01:01:53,448
Rym: Which is fair.

947
01:01:53,528 --> 01:01:54,719
Rym: I'm not saying there's anything wrong with that.

948
01:01:55,542 --> 01:02:04,020
Rym: I read Popular Science for entertainment, not to learn anything in particular, because it didn't teach much past a certain point in its history.

949
01:02:04,100 --> 01:02:06,860
Scott: I always remembered at the barber shop there was always a golf magazine.

950
01:02:07,100 --> 01:02:11,320
Scott: And I didn't golf, but I would read the golf magazine there and it'd be fun.

951
01:02:11,540 --> 01:02:14,360
Scott: But it's like professional golfers were not reading the golf magazine.

952
01:02:17,101 --> 01:02:21,759
Rym: It's the same way at the dentist I would read Reader's Digest because that's what was there.

953
01:02:22,801 --> 01:02:23,157
Scott: Exactly.

954
01:02:23,580 --> 01:02:24,619
Rym: I didn't have a Game Boy yet.

955
01:02:24,920 --> 01:02:26,070
Scott: So there was a whole bunch of those.

956
01:02:26,211 --> 01:02:27,139
Scott: I think they're all dead now.

957
01:02:27,700 --> 01:02:29,568
Scott: There was one called Dr.

958
01:02:29,608 --> 01:02:30,331
Scott: Dobbs Journal.

959
01:02:30,371 --> 01:02:32,259
Scott: I don't know if this still exists or not.

960
01:02:32,841 --> 01:02:37,320
Scott: But it was sort of borderline scientific journal magazine.

961
01:02:39,341 --> 01:02:48,720
Scott: And the only time I read it is because it would be lying around just for free when I was in college in the computer science area.

962
01:02:48,900 --> 01:02:51,700
Scott: They would just have these lying around on tables and I would read it occasionally.

963
01:02:52,341 --> 01:02:56,920
Scott: And it had journal article type stuff in it among ads and other things.

964
01:02:57,381 --> 01:03:00,300
Scott: Mostly to do with actual programming and computer science.

965
01:03:00,641 --> 01:03:08,540
Scott: Oh, here's a cryptography journal article formatted in late LaTeX and everything.

966
01:03:10,180 --> 01:03:16,159
Scott: I'm not sure if it actually was a real journal where you tried to get your research published or not.

967
01:03:16,963 --> 01:03:19,059
Scott: But it sure read like one only with ads in it.

968
01:03:19,561 --> 01:03:21,169
Scott: So that was a thing.

969
01:03:21,189 --> 01:03:23,098
Scott: I don't know if it's still around now.

970
01:03:24,722 --> 01:03:28,240
Rym: It's interesting because I see like that whole class of content itself.

971
01:03:29,360 --> 01:03:40,200
Rym: Like, I don't know, there's a lot of websites like Gizmodo and Engadget and things that basically their articles are the same kind of content that would be in a lot of the PC magazine articles back in the day just on a website.

972
01:03:40,941 --> 01:03:53,480
Rym: But at the same time, the world is so different now that the format of read a magazine that is a curated selection of those articles every month doesn't really fit anymore.

973
01:03:53,680 --> 01:04:01,060
Rym: Like I read the individual articles and individual sites based on specific interests, which is just a radically different paradigm from the pre-internet world.

974
01:04:03,422 --> 01:04:07,580
Scott: So last magazine category I can think of is this one that I got for free.

975
01:04:07,741 --> 01:04:09,640
Scott: I don't remember how the fuck I got it for free.

976
01:04:09,720 --> 01:04:12,897
Scott: I had like a one or two year subscription for zero dollars somehow in the late 90s.

977
01:04:14,062 --> 01:04:16,820
Scott: And it was called Silicon Alley Reporter.

978
01:04:16,960 --> 01:04:18,199
Scott: It doesn't exist now for sure.

979
01:04:18,640 --> 01:04:20,099
Rym: I never encountered that one, I don't think.

980
01:04:21,120 --> 01:04:21,200
Scott: Yeah.

981
01:04:21,240 --> 01:04:27,660
Scott: So it was basically this came out of the 90s, like investment boom kind of deal.

982
01:04:27,881 --> 01:04:28,202
Scott: Right.

983
01:04:28,242 --> 01:04:31,960
Scott: You know, with tech stocks booming up and startups and all that biz.

984
01:04:33,641 --> 01:04:45,400
Scott: And all the articles in it were a lot like the articles you'd read today on like, you know, a hacker news or a tech dirt kind of place, which is talking about startups and business more than it's talking about technology.

985
01:04:46,381 --> 01:04:55,820
Scott: And it had a mix of that sort of like, you know, Silicon Valley disgusting culture, but it was the Silicon Alley reporter.

986
01:04:56,301 --> 01:05:02,860
Scott: And it was basically trying to sort of promote New York as like, hey, in New York, we have a Silicon Alley.

987
01:05:03,041 --> 01:05:05,679
Scott: It's the same kind of thing as Silicon Valley, only in New York.

988
01:05:06,622 --> 01:05:06,843
Scott: Right.

989
01:05:06,863 --> 01:05:10,019
Scott: Kind of trying to drum up that same disgusting culture here.

990
01:05:10,920 --> 01:05:16,100
Rym: You know, I usually say the other thing, Silicon Valley pays people in dreams and in New York, they got to pay you cash.

991
01:05:16,382 --> 01:05:18,700
Rym: That's why nobody likes to talk about Silicon Alley.

992
01:05:19,581 --> 01:05:27,880
Scott: But the Silicon Alley reporter also, right, mixed in sort of like, you know, a lot of like futurist type thinking articles.

993
01:05:28,480 --> 01:05:32,440
Scott: There would always be like one or two in there along with all the other stuff.

994
01:05:32,600 --> 01:05:33,872
Scott: So it's like I was getting it for free.

995
01:05:33,892 --> 01:05:34,559
Scott: I don't know how.

996
01:05:38,084 --> 01:05:40,900
Scott: And you obviously didn't see it at RIT because it had stopped showing up.

997
01:05:41,180 --> 01:05:53,120
Rym: I guess what I miss from this entire space, because we've gone on for well over an hour already, but I miss the computer magazines that would have an interesting project or how to every month.

998
01:05:53,481 --> 01:05:55,879
Scott: Like those make magazine went under.

999
01:05:56,320 --> 01:05:58,718
Scott: Make magazine was a thing you could make.

1000
01:05:59,040 --> 01:06:01,160
Scott: I never got make magazine because it was expensive.

1001
01:06:01,943 --> 01:06:04,020
Scott: If it was cheaper, I would have gotten it.

1002
01:06:04,080 --> 01:06:09,220
Scott: But I really liked all the things that like that make organization was doing, especially the Maker Faire.

1003
01:06:09,784 --> 01:06:11,920
Scott: They just went under even pre-pandemic.

1004
01:06:12,420 --> 01:06:18,020
Rym: I guess what I miss, and I don't think this is just me like having nostalgia and remembering incorrectly.

1005
01:06:18,901 --> 01:06:25,920
Rym: But in those old the PC magazines that had how tos and projects and like guides like, hey, here's how to build a thing or do a cool thing.

1006
01:06:26,963 --> 01:06:29,320
Rym: They did a lot more explanation of the how and why.

1007
01:06:29,842 --> 01:06:34,160
Rym: And the instructions were usually airtight and really well put together with context.

1008
01:06:35,501 --> 01:06:39,800
Rym: Online today, that type of content seems to have split into two directions.

1009
01:06:40,301 --> 01:06:44,520
Rym: It's either here's a bunch of stuff to copy paste into config files with no explanation.

1010
01:06:44,641 --> 01:06:47,159
Rym: That won't work even two months after it comes out.

1011
01:06:47,944 --> 01:06:49,279
Rym: Or it's a video.

1012
01:06:50,601 --> 01:06:53,620
Rym: The least information dense way to present that information.

1013
01:06:54,680 --> 01:07:00,620
Scott: Well, it's also a consequence of just if you have some old computer and you need the computers to help you do something.

1014
01:07:01,383 --> 01:07:05,740
Scott: It's like that computer you're working so much closer to the metal.

1015
01:07:06,381 --> 01:07:07,900
Rym: You really needed that foundation.

1016
01:07:08,520 --> 01:07:10,500
Scott: At least in terms of abstraction layers.

1017
01:07:11,781 --> 01:07:16,259
Scott: It's like you really need someone to tell you like, type this, now type this, now press this key.

1018
01:07:17,281 --> 01:07:22,420
Scott: You don't need that on a current computer because you can describe something to something at the higher abstraction layer.

1019
01:07:22,540 --> 01:07:25,140
Scott: You can be like install that and then do that.

1020
01:07:25,540 --> 01:07:28,460
Scott: It's like you don't have to be like, OK, put the disk in the computer.

1021
01:07:28,561 --> 01:07:30,280
Scott: Now type install, now press enter.

1022
01:07:30,461 --> 01:07:31,076
Scott: You don't have to do that.

1023
01:07:33,082 --> 01:07:39,317
Scott: I do highly recommend going in archive.org and if not the computist, just look for any old computer magazines, 80s, 90s.

1024
01:07:40,660 --> 01:07:44,260
Scott: And it's like that content of that type just doesn't exist anymore.

1025
01:07:45,001 --> 01:07:54,480
Scott: And if you really want to have a lot of fun, get some magazines that go with a particular old computer like an Apple II or like an Amiga.

1026
01:07:54,621 --> 01:07:57,795
Rym: Like Amiga magazines had their Amiga specific nonsense.

1027
01:07:57,835 --> 01:07:58,880
Rym: that was always real fun.

1028
01:07:59,680 --> 01:08:05,480
Scott: And then get yourself an emulator for that old computer and do the stuff in the magazines.

1029
01:08:05,763 --> 01:08:07,599
Scott: You can actually have a really fun time that way.

1030
01:08:08,882 --> 01:08:09,778
Scott: I might in fact do that.

1031
01:08:11,664 --> 01:08:12,528
Rym: I could finally play.

1032
01:08:12,568 --> 01:08:14,739
Rym: I've never messed with an Amiga in my life actually.

1033
01:08:15,540 --> 01:08:15,863
